%I A394791 #49 May 31 2026 21:36:34
%S A394791 3,21,171,903,8001
%N A394791 Smallest number k such that the symmetric representation of sigma(k) has 2*n parts and two parts meet at the center of the Dyck paths.
%C A394791 Conjecture: a(n) is the smallest number k with 2*n 2-dense sublists of divisors of k and 2*A033676(k) + 1 = A033677(k).
%C A394791 a(n) is the smallest number from the intersection of A298856 (the second hexagonal numbers without middle divisors) and the column 2*n of A240062.
%C A394791 To draw the diagram known as the "symmetric representation of sigma(n)" in the first quadrant, the first step is to draw a Dyck path consisting of horizontal and vertical line segments starting from the point [0,n] and ending at the point [n,0]. The length of the k-th line segment is A237593(n,k). The second and final step is to draw another Dyck path consisting of horizontal and vertical line segments starting from the point [0,n-1] to the point [n-1,0]. The length of the k-th line segment is A237593(n-1,k). Between the two Dyck paths there are A237271(n) regions, which are also called "parts." The area of the k-th part is A237270(n,k). Note that the diagram is essentially a map of the terraces on level n (starting from the top) of the stepped pyramid described in A245092. For further information see A237593 and A262626. See also the example below.
%e A394791 a(1) = 3 is the smallest number from the intersection of A298856 and A239929.
%e A394791 a(2) = 21 is the smallest number from the intersection of A298856 and A280107.
%e A394791 a(3) = 171 is the smallest number from the intersection of A298856 and A320511.
%e A394791 .
%e A394791 For n = 2 we have that a(2) = 21 because 21 is the smallest number k whose symmetric representation of sigma(k) has 2*n = 2*2 = 4 parts (or regions) and two parts meet at the center of the Dyck paths as shown below in the first quadrant:
