%e A394791 Example from the conjecture: for n = 5 we have that a(5) = 8001 because 8001 is the smallest number k with 2*n = 2*5 = 10 2-dense sublists of divisors of k and 2*A033676(k) + 1 = A033677(k) since the central divisors of 8001 are A033676(8001) = 63 and A033677(8001) = 127 and we can see that 2*63 + 1 = 127. The 12 divisors and the 10 2-dense sublists of divisors of 8001 are as follows [with sublists in brackets]: [1], [3], [7, 9], [21], [63], [127], [381], [889, 1143], [2667], [8001].
%Y A394791 Row 1 of A395156.
%Y A394791 Other sequences where two parts meet at the center of the Dyck path are A191363, A262259, A264104, A298856, A392197 and A395156.
%Y A394791 Cf. A000203, A014105, A033676, A033677, A071561, A174973 (2-dense numbers), A207375, A237270, A237271, A237593 (Dyck paths), A239929, A240062, A245092, A262626, A280107, A298856, A320511, A384222 (2-dense sublists).
